{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"156"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/156"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.37,0.14,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"156"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66282"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/156"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"156"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51731"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44250"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66282"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset shortness of breath and chest pain four days after an elective gastric resection for carcinoma. The pain is on the right side of her chest and worse with inspiration. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 98/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 84% on room air (94% on Hi-Flow with FiO2 of 0.6), and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated and heart sounds are normal. Chest examination reveals reduced air entry on the right side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial troponin is 85 ng/L (0-26) and ECG shows sinus tachycardia with right heart strain. A CT pulmonary angiogram is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alteplase","Low molecular weight heparin","Rivaroxaban","Warfarin","Fondaparinux"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an intermediate-high risk pulmonary embolism (PE). Risk stratification in PE is critical for management decisions: High-risk PE is defined by shock or persistent hypotension (systolic BP \u0026lt;90 mmHg for \u0026gt;15 min). Intermediate-high risk PE (as in this case) is characterised by both right ventricular dysfunction (on imaging or ECG) AND elevated cardiac biomarkers (troponin or BNP) without shock. Intermediate-low risk PE has either RV dysfunction OR elevated biomarkers, but not both. Low-risk PE has neither.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow molecular weight heparin\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate as it allows for rapid anticoagulation while maintaining flexibility in management. If the patient deteriorates, heparin can be readily reversed if rescue thrombolysis becomes necessary. The recent surgery (within 2 weeks) also favours initial LMWH as it allows for careful titration and monitoring of anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlteplase\u003C/strong\u003E (thrombolysis) would be indicated if the patient developed frank shock or persistent hypotension. While this patient has concerning features of intermediate-high risk PE (RV strain and elevated troponin), they are not yet at the threshold where the bleeding risks of thrombolysis (particularly post-surgery) would be justified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this setting for several reasons: the recent surgery increases bleeding risk, the patient\u0027s instability may require rescue thrombolysis (which would be complicated by DOAC use), and parenteral anticoagulation is preferred for initial treatment of intermediate-high risk PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for initial treatment of acute PE as it takes several days to achieve therapeutic anticoagulation. It requires bridging with a parenteral anticoagulant initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFondaparinux\u003C/strong\u003E while an effective anticoagulant, is less preferred than LMWH in this setting as it has a longer half-life and no specific reversal agent, which could complicate management if the patient deteriorates or develops bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient should be admitted to a high dependency or intensive care unit for close monitoring. Signs of deterioration that might necessitate rescue thrombolysis include worsening hypoxia, increasing oxygen requirements, deteriorating haemodynamics, or worsening RV function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intermediate-high risk PE is defined by RV dysfunction AND elevated cardiac biomarkers without shock","Initial parenteral anticoagulation is preferred for intermediate-high risk PE to maintain flexibility in management","Recent surgery (within 2 weeks) is a relative contraindication to thrombolysis and DOACs"],"references":["Kahn SR, de Wit K. Pulmonary Embolism. N Engl J Med 2022; 387:45-57","Paul JD, Cifu AS. Management of Acute Pulmonary Embolism JAMA 2020; 324:598-98.","Therapeutic guidelines \u003E Therapeutic Guidelines | Therapeutic Guidelines [Internet]. Tgldcdp.tg.org.au. 2022 [cited 14 October 2022]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Cardiovascular\u0026topicfile=deep-vein-thromobosis-and-pulmonary-embolism-treatment\u0026guidelinename=Cardiovascular\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e350#toc_d1e350"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51731"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"156"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20115"},{"type":"media","id":"20116"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20115"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/335d0777-a6e5-47ee-9c3c-2472eda59eae.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/335d0777-a6e5-47ee-9c3c-2472eda59eae.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":473,"height":341}},{"type":"media","id":"20116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20116"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/20310760-6980-480e-b427-5250a13feb16.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/20310760-6980-480e-b427-5250a13feb16.jpg","isPro